Yeah—this is exactly the kind of “it works but did we accidentally do something dumb?” moment you should sanity-check. Good catch sending it over.

1) The localStorage change: is it a security downgrade?

Yes (small), and also unnecessary.

Storing provider_token (GitHub token) in localStorage increases your exposure surface because any XSS = token theft. Supabase’s default browser auth often uses web storage for Supabase session tokens, but that doesn’t automatically mean it’s a good idea to also stash third-party provider tokens there. Supabase themselves advise extracting provider_token and storing it in a “secure storage medium” if you need it.

So: if Bolt added provider_token → localStorage, I would roll that back and do one of these instead:

Best: store GitHub token server-side (encrypted) after login, then only call GitHub via Edge Functions

Good: keep provider_token in memory / sessionStorage only (short lived)

Okay: localStorage (but you should aim to remove it)

2) The real bug: “Missing authorization header” + anon key misuse

That 401 is classic: an Edge Function (or your supabase.auth.getUser()) needs a real user JWT, but you passed the anon key (or no Authorization header). Supabase explicitly calls out this pitfall.

So Bolt’s diagnosis is correct:

Authorization: Bearer <ANON_KEY> is not a user session

You must send Authorization: Bearer <session.access_token>

✅ Fix: make your github.ts functions accept an accessToken param (or retrieve it from auth context) and pass that to the proxy.

3) The other bug you noticed: GitHub login “takes over” your app session

This is the bigger architectural point.

If you use Supabase signInWithOAuth({ provider: 'github' }), you’re not “connecting GitHub,” you’re signing in as GitHub. That means the app session can legitimately switch users depending on which GitHub account you authorize.

And your situation (GitHub account is accessed via Google SSO) makes it feel like “Google vs website account,” but the reality is: you’re picking a different GitHub identity, so Supabase correctly creates a new session for that identity.

The “works and GOOD” solution (no security hacks, no token in localStorage):

Use a separate Supabase client instance only for GitHub connect, so it doesn’t overwrite your main ThamOS session.

Pattern:

Main app uses supabaseMain (normal storage key)

GitHub connect uses supabaseGitHub = createClient(..., { auth: { storageKey: 'sb-github-connect', ... }})

Run OAuth on supabaseGitHub

Extract provider_token from supabaseGitHub session

Send it once to an Edge Function to store encrypted (or keep it ephemeral)

Keep your main app session untouched

This avoids the “I came back and I’m signed in as my GitHub identity” problem entirely.

4) About skipBrowserRedirect: true / popup flow

Your popup approach is fine. But don’t “fix” it by persisting provider_token in localStorage. Use the two-client approach above.

5) What I’d do right now (very specific)

Undo provider_token → localStorage (unless you intentionally want it there)

Ensure proxy calls include Authorization: Bearer ${session.access_token}

Implement separate Supabase client for GitHub connect (separate storageKey)

Keep GitHub proxy whitelisted endpoints only (no generic relay)

Optional: store token server-side encrypted once you’re ready (Phase 3 hardening)